Based on the reference materials and detailed specifications, here's the complete implementation:

```cpp
#include <hexi/pmc/buffer_adaptor.h>
#include <vector>
#include <cstdint>

void peek_data_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, void* data, std::size_t length) {
    // Use the non-template copy() method to copy bytes without advancing read pointer
    buffer.copy(data, length);
}

template<typename T>
void peek_value_from_buffer(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, T& value) {
    // Use the template copy() method to copy a single value without advancing read pointer
    buffer.copy(&value);
}

bool peek_and_compare(hexi::pmc::buffer_adaptor<std::vector<std::byte>>& buffer, const void* expected, std::size_t length) {
    // Create a temporary buffer to hold the peeked data
    std::vector<std::byte> temp_buffer(length);

    // Use copy() to peek data without advancing read pointer
    buffer.copy(temp_buffer.data(), length);

    // Compare the peeked data with expected data
    for (std::size_t i = 0; i < length; ++i) {
        if (static_cast<const std::byte*>(expected)[i] != temp_buffer[i]) {
            return false;
        }
    }

    return true;
}
```

## Key Implementation Points:

1. **`peek_data_from_buffer`**: Uses the non-template `copy()` method that takes a `void*` destination and `std::size_t` length to copy raw bytes without advancing the read pointer.

2. **`peek_value_from_buffer`**: Uses the template `copy()` method that takes a typed pointer (`T*`) to copy a single value of type `T` without advancing the read pointer.

3. **`peek_and_compare`**: 
   - Creates a temporary buffer to hold the peeked data
   - Uses `copy()` to peek data without consuming it
   - Compares each byte of the peeked data with the expected data
   - Returns `true` if all bytes match, `false` otherwise

All implementations correctly use the `copy()` method from `buffer_adaptor` which, according to the reference materials, copies data without advancing the read pointer (unlike the `read()` method which advances the read pointer).

